Congratulations to @beckyarnettt in Ontario, Canada for winning the FHF Friday Contest! Rebecca’s question for Patrick was, “Thank you again for taking the time to answer my question! I am so excited to have the opportunity to have you look at my home. I absolutely adore all of your work. Please find below numerous pictures of the house from different angles. Please let me know if you need additional photos or information. Layouts are also included below to help you visualize the shape of the house. The first layout is from when we bought the home. The next three pictures show the layout with some renovations we have already completed. Our hope for the future addition is to create a large ensuite bathroom and closet for the master bedroom on the second floor. If we carry the addition up to the third floor as well, our plan is to add a third bedroom on the third floor. In case it affects your recommendations, our eventual plan is to completely re-landscape the backyard and put in a pool. We also plan to enlarge the kitchen all the way to the back of the house (by getting rid of the bedroom there, although we may keep a small laundry and bathroom where they are currently located). If we are able to create a third bedroom on the third floor, we may also get rid of Bedroom 2 on the second floor and try to recreate the original grand staircase there, which has unfortunately been removed.”

Watch the video to hear about Patrick’s advice for Rebecca. Follow us on Instagram to participate in our FHF Contest for a chance to ask Patrick a question of your own and win a signed copy of our book, Timeless.

Congratulations to @sugarsawdustglue in Potomac Falls, VA for winning the FHF Friday Contest! Nina’s question for Patrick was, “We recently added a flagstone patio to our side and backyard, but feel that the back side of our home is an eyesore.  We have a brick-textured concrete foundation, a set of French doors (leading to the basement rec room) that are off-centered under this unusual bump-out from the main floor, with a “door-to-nowhere”. The door on the bump-out leads to the master bedroom and I would like to eventually replace it with either a window or a gas fireplace. My husband and I would very much appreciate suggestions for making this area more visually appealing.”

Watch the video to hear about Patrick’s advice for Nina. Follow us on Instagram to participate in our FHF Contest for a chance to ask Patrick a question of your own and win a signed copy of our book, Timeless.

Congratulations to @joseph_ward437 in Glen Arm, MD for winning the FHF Friday Contest! Joseph’s question for Patrick was, “Hi Patrick. Thank you so much for doing this contest and allowing me to ask you a question. I was hoping you could talk a little bit about when you knew our firm was going to grow into what it is today. Was there a pivotal project that you feel was your breakout success and got you more clients. Was there a time where you thought all hope was lost but you managed to turn it around. And also, can you give some advice for someone planning to start their own firm in the future? Thank you!”

Watch the video to hear about Patrick’s response. Follow us on Instagram to participate in our FHF Contest for a chance to ask Patrick a question of your own and win a signed copy of our book, Timeless.

node.title: FHF | Building Your Firm—Success and Obstacles

Congratulations to @rmarks04 in Weston, MA for winning the FHF Friday Contest! Rachel’s question for Patrick was, “This made my week!!! Thank you for being everyone’s favorite Instagram follow, and for doing this amazing contest every week. We own an 1896 American foursquare with very similar bones to your incredible “Mystic Lake Overlook” project in Winchester. The exterior still makes our hearts flutter, but the foyer feels a little blah, cramped, and not-so-functional for our young family. We need some mudroom space! We have no attached garage, so the front door is our only real entry to the house for us & for guests. It currently opens to a small foyer with the staircase to the left and an office to the right. There’s a tiny coat closet tucked beneath the stairs, but the shoes & coats usually end up on the floor. We’ve thought about opening up the wall between the foyer & the office to create a mudroom nook. How would you reconfigure to create some historically-appropriate “wow factor” AND function? I will send you a DM including a floor plan. Thank you Patrick & team!!”

Watch the video to hear about Patrick’s recommendations on how to create a more functional foyer while maintaining the historic character of their home. Follow us on Instagram to participate in our FHF Contest for a chance to ask Patrick a question of your own and win a signed copy of our book, Timeless.

node.text:
Congratulations to @nelsoncm13 in Marietta, GA for winning the FHF Friday Contest! Colleen’s question for Patrick was, “Thank you for the honor and opportunity to receive your time and feedback.
To give you some background, my husband and I purchased our home about 3.5 years ago and fell in love with its classic style and private spacious backyard…My question for you is, how would you add on to the back of the house? We would like to do an addition behind the garage to the first and second levels…I love our backyard but I don't always love how our home looks from behind and I feel like this is our chance to bring backyard appeal…”

Watch the video to hear about Patrick’s recommendations on how to improve Colleen’s rear façade while planning for an addition. Follow us on Instagram to participate in our FHF Contest for a chance to ask Patrick a question of your own and win a signed copy of our book, Timeless.

node.title: FHF | Adding an Addition and Character to Colleen’s Rear Facade

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC in Chatham, Massachusetts. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: On today’s blog, we’re covering go-to materials for outdoor living spaces. From hardscape to softscape and elements in between, we highlight our choices for for timeless, durable and beautiful exterior programming. Find the link in today’s Stories.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC on August 18, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and tree.

node.text: On Edgartown Harbor, this home’s water-facing side makes the most of its seaside setting, meeting the clients’ request for a quintessential beach house designed for indoor-outdoor entertaining. French doors in the kitchen and living room open to a covered porch that serves as an alfresco living and dining area, complete with a working fireplace.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC in Edgartown Village Historic District. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
This Edgartown residence was compromised structurally and aesthetically.  As such, it was taken down to its foundation almost entirely, and a new home was erected based on nearby eighteenth-century Greek Revival captain’s houses. The property was meticulously designed to be thematically respectful of the neighborhood and the harbor beyond.
Builder: @colonial_reproductions 
Landscape: @donaromasmv 
Photographer: @gregpremru

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC in Edgartown, Massachusetts. May be an image of tree and outdoors.

node.text:
Timeless exterior elements can elevate a home's sense of character.  Here, an execution of the Edgartown Fence, a picket with rail across the top, with an arbor and gate surrounded by lush hydrangea.
Photographer: @taylormahearn

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC on August 15, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text: Although waterfront and on ample property, this gambrel-roofed, shingle-style, nineteenth-century house felt dark, inward facing, and cramped. To accommodate the clients’ request for more space and outdoor programming, two wings were added to mirror the original house, creating implied symmetry that maintains the exterior’s historic appearance, even from the water.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC in Cohasset, Massachusetts. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
In this new Cohasset build, a side porch links to an ocean-view pool with a cabana and an outdoor kitchen, and a simple boardwalk connects to the shore. In summer, residents spend their days at the beach or pool or in the backyard, while a glass-enclosed porch provides water views and warmth in winter.

Builder: @colcloughconstruction 
Interior Designer: @katierosenfeld 
Landscape: @seanpapichlandscape 
Photographer: @sabrinacolequinn

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC on August 13, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: The goal for the design of this new house—in a protected wetland conservation area on Edgartown’s Katama Bay—was to create a home that would feel warmly romantic and cozy, and at the same time very much open to the marshland and harbor in the near distance.  Here, a view of the rear of the property and pool looking out onto the glistening water.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC on August 12, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and brick wall.

node.text: Abundant window boxes can imbue a home with character.  On  shingled properties, we recommend window boxes in the same hue as fully operational shutters with appropriate holdbacks and hardware for timeless appeal.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC in Cohasset, Massachusetts. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
At this new waterfront shingle-style residence in Cohasset, the bright coral family entrance hints at the vibrant interiors within.

Builder: @colcloughconstruction 
Interior Designer: @katierosenfeld 
Landscape: @seanpapichlandscape 
Photographer: @michaeljleephotography

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC on August 09, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: This new build overlooking the Atlantic from the southern tip of Rhode Island masks its size within a carefully conceived façade. The pieces of its design, including an entrance nestled between what look like enclosed porches under gabled dormers, minimize the scale while accommodating significant square footage.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC on August 08, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text: This expansive multigenerational family retreat set on 215 acres of waterfront rolling farmland takes cues from the agrarian landscape in its design.  While the home's square footage and modern programming is significant, care was taken to build upon traditional aesthetics and all but disappear into the surroundings.  Here, the pool area embraced by the main house includes alfresco living rooms, an outdoor kitchen with grills and a bar, and a hot tub.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Patrick Ahearn Architect LLC on August 07, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and tree.

node.text: The gambrel roofline on this waterfront residence allows for interior volume our clients desired and an exterior scale befitting the Vineyard Haven Harbor.  Expansive views are captured by walls of windows on the first floor and both french doors and decking above.
